SIMPLE: forego
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Forego
<hw>Fore*go"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Forewent 2</conjf>; <pos>p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Foregone</conjf> <pr>(?; 115)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Foregoing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[See <er>Forgo</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To quit; to relinquish; to leave.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Stay at the third cup, or <qex>forego</qex> the place.</q>
<rj><qau>Herbert.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To relinquish the enjoyment or advantage of; to give
up; to resign; to renounce; -- said of a thing already enjoyed, or of
one within reach, or anticipated.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All my patrimony,,⟦br⟧
If need be, I am ready to <qex>forego</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy lovers must their promised heaven <qex>forego</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Keble.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[He] never <qex>forewent</qex> an opportunity of honest
profit.</q> <rj><qau>R. L. Stevenson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Forgo</xex> is the better spelling etymologically,
but the word has been confused with <er>Forego</er>, to go
before.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Forego</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Forego
<hw>Fore*go"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>foreg⟦amac⟧n</ets>;
<ets>fore</ets> + <ets>g⟦amac⟧n</ets> to go; akin to G.
<ets>vorgehen</ets> to go before, precede. See <er>Go</er>, <pos>v.
i.</pos>]</ety> <def>To go before; to precede; -- used especially in the
present and past participles.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Pleasing remembrance of a thought <qex>foregone</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For which the very mother's face <qex>forewent</qex>⟦br⟧
The mother's special patience.</q> <rj><qau>Mrs.
Browning.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Foregone conclusion</b></col>, <cd>a conclusion which has
preceded argument or examination; a predetermined
conclusion.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Foregoer</ent>⟦br⟧
